Topic: Form Configuration, Fields, Form Builder, Templates, Dot-Walking



1. What Are Forms in ServiceNow?

Forms display a single record from a table.
Each record contains fields, and forms show those fields in a structured layout.

Why forms matter:
  Users view or edit important data
  Each user may need different data depending on their role

  Example:
    Major Incident Manager → sees Major Incident tab
    HR Payroll Specialist → sees salary data not visible to others



2. How ServiceNow Organizes Data

  Uses a database structure
  Tables store data (e.g., User, Incident, HR Case)
  Records = each row
  Fields = data inside the record (e.g., Department, Email)
  Depending on roles, users see different information



3. Form Elements

Forms include:
  Fields
  Sections
  Formatters
  Related Lists
  UI Actions
  Activity Stream
  Tabs

These help users navigate and interact with records efficiently.



4. Field Types

ServiceNow supports 30+ field types, for example:
  Reference
  Date & Time
  String
  Choice
  True/False

When creating a new record:
  Make sure you’re using the correct view
  Some fields must be filled before saving
  Changing views may require saving/discarding changes



5. Ways to Modify a Form

Three main tools:

1. Form Builder
2. Form Design
3. Form Layout

⚠ Avoid adding the same editable field in multiple form sections
This can break UI Policies or Data Policies.



6. Form Builder (Main Tool for Admins)
  Form Builder allows you to:
    Add fields
    Move fields
    Delete fields
    Add related lists
    Select layouts
    Apply rules

  Admins can also configure:
    UI Policies
    Access Control Rules
    Client Scripts
    Business Rules
    Workspace View Rules

You can configure field attributes through the Configuration Panel.



7. Dot-Walking on Forms

Dot-walking lets you display data from a related table.

Steps:
  Click Add Related Field
  Select field from reference table
  Add to form
  Save → field appears on form



8. Adding New Fields to Tables

Steps:
  Go to System Definition → Tables
  Select table
  Add new field under Columns tab
  Return to form and place field using Form Builder
  


9. Formatters

Examples of built-in formatters:
  Activity formatter
  Parent breadcrumbs
  Approval summarizer
  CI Relations
  Process flow formatter
T hese add functionality to the form.



10. Related Lists on Forms

Using the List Collector, you can:
  Add related lists
  Remove related lists
  Reorder related lists
  Ensure the correct form view is selected.



11. Personalizing a Form (User-Specific)

To personalize:
  Open a record
  Click Personalize Form icon
  Hide/show fields (only non-mandatory fields)
  Reset hidden fields if needed

Personalized layout persists for that user only.

 

12. Form Templates

Templates help users fill common fields automatically.

Features:
  Show a check mark if updated

  Can be created for:
    Incident
    Change
    HR Case
    Any table

  No limit to number of templates

  But too many templates become difficult to manage

⚠ Only certain groups should create templates
→ to avoid bypassing mandatory fields, UI policies, workflows

Admins can:

  Set scripts to automatically apply templates
  Make templates available to groups/users



13. Templates in Workspace

Workspace forms use a different layout:
  Form is in Details tab
  Fields in Details Panel
  Activity Stream in a separate panel

To share a workspace template
  Use magnifying glass
  Choose groups
  Save template

⚠ Deleted templates cannot be recovered.



14. Creating a Custom Form Template

Steps:
  Go to Templates Pane
  Click Plus (+)
  Name the template
  Add/remove fields
  Save

In your lab, you only need to add a new field to a form.


